 Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Dundas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Scottish (Angus and Midlothian) and Irish (Fermanagh): habitational name from Dundas, a place near Edinburgh, Scotland, which is named from Gaelic <i>dùn</i> ‘hill’ + <i>deas</i> ‘south’.","History: A family of this name is descended from Gospatrick, Earl of March (died 1139), whose grandson was Helia de Dundas."],"variants":[]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"George de Dundas was born about 1290, in West Lothian, Scotland, United Kingdom as the son of Sir Hugh de Dundas. He married Baroness Agnes Forrester in 1323. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. He died on 11 August 1332, in Dupplin, Perthshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, at the age of 43."},"et":{"Abt 1290–11 August 1332":"umbes 1290–11. august 1332","1290–1332":"1290–1332","–Female":"Surnud","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1324–1363":"1324–1363","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1363":"1363","1270":"1270","ABT 1329":"umbes 1329","1290":"1290","1324":"1324","1323":"1323","Abt 1310":"umbes 1310","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","11 August 1332":"11. august 1332","1364":"1364","Abt 1290":"umbes 1290","1329":"1329","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Scotland","Dundas, Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Scotland","Dundas, West Lothian, Scotland":"West Lothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","West Lothian, Scotland":"West Lothian, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Dupplin Moor, Scotland":"Dupplin, Perthshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1290–11 August 1332":"noin 1290–11. elokuuta 1332","1290–1332":"1290–1332","–Female":"Kuollut","1310–1364":"1310–1364","1324–1363":"1324–1363","1270–1329":"1270–1329","1363":"1363","1270":"1270","ABT 1329":"noin 1329","1290":"1290","1324":"1324","1323":"1323","Abt 1310":"noin 1310","1310":"1310","1332":"1332","11 August 1332":"11. elokuuta 1332","1364":"1364","Abt 1290":"noin 1290","1329":"1329","Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linlithgowshire, Scotland","Dundas, Linlithgowshire, Scotland":"Linli